<body>

<center>
<b>CREATE/UPDATE STATION OBSERVATION SIGMA FACTORS</b>
<p>Editor: EDITSOS
</center>
<hr width="100%">

<a name="DATUM"      default="DATUM."></a>
<a name="COORD"      default=""></a>
<a name="NEWFILE"    default=""></a>
<a name="STAWGT_HLP" default="%% %% %% %% %%"></a>
<a name="STALST"     default=""></a>

<p><b>GENERAL DESCRIPTION </b>
<p>
This file provides station observation sigma factors for a list of
stations and for specific measurement types. This
input panel helps you to create or to edit this type of files.
<br>
To create a new station observation sigma factor file specify a new
filename in the file selection dialogue. In this case you will be asked to
select an existing coordinate file. Select a subset of the stations in
this file to generate a template for the new station sigma factor file.

<p><i>Remark:</i>
The end of the station observation sigma factor file is indicated by a
blank line. Lines below the blank line are ignored. If you use this
input mask to edit a station sigma factor file these additional lines
will be lost. If you want to keep them in the file you have to use an
external text file editor.
<br>
A station observation sigma factor file may also be created by the program
<a href="PGMLST.HLP#RESRMS">RESRMS</a> (see option
<a href="RESRMS.HLP#STAWGTRS">STAWGTRS</a>).

<p><a href="/$X/DOC/EXAMPLE.SOS">Example</a>

<p><hr>

<p><b>CREATE A NEW STATION OBSERVATION SIGMA FACTOR FILE</b>

<a name="STASEL" default=""></a>
<p><b>Station list for sigma factor file:</b>
Select the stations (taken from the coordinate file specified before)
you want to add to the template of the station observation sigma factor file.

<a name="PHASE" default="0"></a>
<a name="CODE"  default="0"></a>
<a name="RANGE" default="0"></a>
<p><b>TYPES OF OBSERVATIONS</b>
<p>
Choose the type(s) of observation:
<ul>
<li><b>Sigma factors for phase observations</b>
<li><b>Sigma factors for code observations</b>
<li><b>Sigma factors for range observations</b>
</ul>
For each station and each observation type selected above there will be one
record in the new station weight file, initialized with a sigma factor of 1.000.

<p><hr>

<p><b>STATION OBSERVATION SIGMA FACTOR FILE</b>

<a name="STAWGTRS" default=""></a>
<p><b>Filename:</b>
The absolute path and the name of the station observation sigma factor file is
given here.

<a name="TITLE" default=""></a>
<p><b>Title:</b>
Enter a title line. The title will be saved in the header of the file.

<a name="STAWGT" default="%% %% %% %% %%"></a>
<p><b>Station name:</b>
Enter the station name.

<p><b>Meatyp:</b>
Enter the measurement type (type of observations). Allowed are the strings
<tt>PHASE</tt>, <tt>CODE</tt>, and <tt>RANGE</tt> to indicate the corresponding
measurement type.

<p><b>Sigma factor:</b>
Enter the sigma factor for each of the stations and each measurement type.
A sigma factor&nbsp;<i>n</i> larger than 1.000 corresponds to a down-weighting
of the observations by <i>n<sup>2</sup></i>.

<p><b>Valid from</b> - <b>to:</b>
The sigma factors are valid for the time window specified here. An empty
input field indicates an open boundary of the time window.

<p><hr>

